WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
 Welcome to another code walkthrough for C programming for everybody.

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:13.200
 In this code walkthrough, we are going to compare how Guido implemented list in the earliest versions of Python

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:19.400
 versus how I implemented list while teaching Chapter 6 of Carnegie and Ritchie.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:25.400
 And so this was, if you watched the video of my interview with Guido Van Rossum,

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.400
 this was like my greatest, like, revelation. Like, what?

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:41.800
 And so the big revelation is, is that Python's list object in, you know, Python 0.01 was an array of pointers.

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:48.600
 And if we look at the Carnegie and Ritchie list item, this was a linked list. I did a linked list.

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:56.400
 And so the actual KR list struct has a pointer to the head and the tail of its linked list and account.

00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:02.400
 And again, this is classic linked list. And to some degree, while I was teaching this in Carnegie and Ritchie Chapter 6,

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:08.400
 I was really teaching you linked lists and using the Python list abstraction to teach it.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:17.000
 And so we have two data structures. We have this node, which just has a pointer to a text saved and a pointer to the next one.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.800
 So this is like classic linked list. I'm not going to I'm not going to go through that again.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:28.300
 So you just go back and watch the Chapter 6 stuff. And I talk about linked lists all the time.

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:34.300
 But that's not how Python does it, did it or does it.

00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:43.900
 And it's not clear to me exactly why, but he I think he was just trying to build the simplest possible data structure.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:50.500
 And we'll look at some code and you'll see that there is a certain simplicity, like already in just the struct definition.

00:01:50.500 --> 00:02:00.600
 We see the struct P1 list. There's only one of them. If it's a linked list, you have sort of a struct for the node and a struct for the list itself.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:10.000
 The constructor P1 list new. Well, we're just going to malloc the object and then we're going to say, OK, let's allocate.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.500
 Let's allocate to an array of pointers to characters.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:26.800
 And so so if we look at the struct P1 list and we see char star star items, that is syntax for a array of pointers.

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.600
 OK, and so you think of each pointer as either 32 bits in the old days or 64 bits in the modern days.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:42.600
 So that's an array. And so so what I'm doing in this P items equals malloc open print P alloc times size of char star.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:51.800
 That means I'm allocating two elements that are pointers, which means, again, two times 64 bits in the modern world.

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:59.600
 And noting that I have two in there and length, which is the Python view of the number of items is zero.

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:03.000
 So we've got we've got space for two and we have zero.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:10.900
 And that's an array that we know Alec tells us how long the array is and length tells us how much of the array we've used.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:15.200
 And just to go back, I'll try not to compare and contrast too much.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:23.700
 But just think about the complexity of linked lists the way I did them in Kernighan and Ritchie, my Kernighan and Ritchie Chapter 6.

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:28.900
 You have this thing called head. You have this thing called tail, which is null and count is zero.

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:33.500
 And again, for those of us who know linked list, this is obvious.

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:37.600
 It's what you do. But an array is simpler than a linked list.

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:41.600
 And so, you know, there we go.

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:47.700
 OK, OK, OK, OK. So that's what we're what we've got when we're done with our constructor.

00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:54.200
 We've got an array of two pointers, two characters. Allocated to and length one.

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:57.900
 So let's go take a look at let's take a look at the main code right now.

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:05.800
 And so the key to this main code is that in a sense, here's the Kernighan and Ritchie main code,

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:12.700
 because this is like an interface and an abstraction, the main code should be pretty much the same.

00:04:12.700 --> 00:04:18.200
 And the main code pretty much is the same, meaning that we create a linked list, we append some stuff to it,

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:22.100
 we print the list, we check the length, we look something up and then we delete it.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:30.400
 And we do both things because below the abstraction, below the interface, both of these implementations,

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:38.300
 both the KR list and the P1 list are supposed to provide to us, the caller, the same abstraction.

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:43.900
 We can append, we can print, we can check the length, we can check the index and we can delete it.

00:04:43.900 --> 00:04:46.000
 And it does not matter what the implementation is.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:54.900
 And that's so that's more the builders of the Python runtime get to decide how to do this because we've got a contract with them.

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:58.400
 Again, an interface. So let's just take a look at the code.

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:00.800
 We're going to add hello world to our list and print it.

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:02.600
 Then we're going to add catchphrase and print it.

00:05:02.600 --> 00:05:05.100
 Then we're going to add Brian and print it.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.800
 And then we're going to say, how big is it?

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:11.500
 And then we're going to ask, where is Brian in there and where is Bob in there?

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:13.300
 And then we're going to delete it.

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:19.100
 And if you look at the run, you see, you know, the list starts out as hello world and the list is hello world catchphrase.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:24.400
 And we'll see what this extending because we started with two slots in our array.

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:26.800
 And for the first two, you didn't have to get bigger.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:30.200
 But then we're like, oh, wow, we're running out of space.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.200
 So we got to like extend this array.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.000
 We'll show that code in a bit.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.600
 But then we end up with three things in the list.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:40.800
 Again, that's not our job as the caller, three things in the list.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:47.700
 And Brian is in position two, which zero, one, two, hello world is zero, catchphrase is one and Brian is two.

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:51.200
 And Bob is not there. So we get back a negative one.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:55.000
 Pretty stuff. OK, so let's take a look at the append code,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.400
 because this is where the fun happens.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.700
 So here's the append code.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:05.500
 So let's take a look at the let's go back.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:11.500
 How I taught you append, you know, a month or so ago.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.700
 And so so again, you got this.

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:16.900
 The lecture has pictures of all this. Right.

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:23.100
 So if you're appending, if it's empty, your self head is new.

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:29.700
 If the self tail is not equal, no, then self tail next equals new and then self tail new equals new.

00:06:29.700 --> 00:06:35.100
 So that's just like you got to draw the picture and add the little arrows and away you go.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:37.700
 And then you can save the string itself.

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:44.900
 But now we look at the P1 list and we we have to extend it if necessary.

00:06:44.900 --> 00:06:51.300
 Right. So if self length, i.e. is greater than self Alex.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:55.300
 So we allocated two in the first in the in the constructor.

00:06:55.300 --> 00:07:02.500
 And then if the length is two, we don't have enough space because our next one would be sub two.

00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:07.100
 And that you can have sub zero and sub one in a two long array.

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:14.800
 And so all we're going to do then is we're going to have chunking and Guido mentioned chunking in the video.

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:21.800
 We're going to chunk it to add 10. And so we're going to basically extend from two to 10.

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:28.000
 So we're going to add 10. We're going to increase the alloc size and then we're going to call realloc.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:37.100
 And realloc is going to take the array of items and say how big that was, free it, move it, whatever.

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:41.200
 Extend it depending on what realloc is, how realloc is working.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:48.900
 And we're going to say, OK, we want to have 12 of these things now, 12 and that becomes our new items.

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:54.900
 Now, realloc will also so there's two things in it and we extended 12.

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:57.300
 realloc will copy the two things.

00:07:57.300 --> 00:08:04.100
 So we don't have to do any copying because realloc copies the first two things because it knows that items is too long.

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:08.200
 And so it copies the first two things and then gives us 10 more.

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:10.400
 So there's no copy code here.

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:17.000
 And so I think Guido really liked the realloc and a lot of C programmers don't like realloc and he did.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.600
 He's like, look, realloc says it's going to do this and I want to do this.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:24.300
 So realloc, realloc, do your job.

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:33.600
 And so I think back to my own time as a software developer, I just felt because again, we were taught linked list, linked list, linked list.

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:40.500
 I just didn't think about realloc as a useful thing and Guido clearly felt like realloc is the answer.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:44.400
 And it lets him have this simple array mentality.

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:48.400
 So you just realloc it and say, look, here's an array of this two, I want it to be 12.

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:50.000
 Help me and we're done.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.800
 And so that's really simple code.

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:55.400
 I think very easy to understand.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:59.000
 And then we make a save string.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:05.600
 And then we just add at the end of the array self length, which in this case is sub 2, is that string.

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:07.800
 And then we add one to the length.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:09.700
 So this code is really simple.

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:17.900
 And if you were doing debug print, you don't really need any addresses because if you recall when I'm printing in all my linked list stuff,

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:23.800
 so that you can debug it and redraw your lines and figure everything out, I'm printing addresses out all the time.

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:25.400
 But no, this is just a position.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:28.900
 So this is the 0, the 1, and now the 2 in this case.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:32.700
 And so that's where you see when it says extending from 2 to 12.

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:40.300
 That's as a side effect of adding the third item to a list that was pre-allocated with two slots.

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:41.600
 OK.

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:44.300
 And that's it.

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:50.000
 But let's take a look at the print code, right?

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:56.500
 Let's look at the print code for both of them.

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.600
 This is KRList print.

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:04.400
 Let's take a look at the print code in Guido van Rossum's version.

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:06.800
 OK.

00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:13.000
 So the key to this is the for loop in P1_List_Print.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:25.000
 The for loop is for i equals 0, semicolon, i less than self length, let's take that blank out, i less than self length, i plus plus.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:34.700
 That is like really basic chapter 4, chapter 5 stuff in Kernighan and Ritchie.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.700
 So it's just an array.

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:39.400
 So you write a simple incremented for loop.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:42.500
 It's fast, cash efficient.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:45.100
 It's beautifully simple, right?

00:10:45.100 --> 00:10:48.300
 So in this print, this is obvious.

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:58.800
 Now, when I showed you the same thing in Kernighan and Ritchie Chapter 6, I had this for in KRList_Print.

00:10:58.800 --> 00:11:05.100
 It says for ker equals self arrow head, ker not equal null, ker equals ker next.

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:06.900
 And I apologize for this line.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:12.100
 I'm like, you will eventually write this because it's an idiom.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:19.100
 You will write this quite naturally and it'll make a lot of sense to you, right?

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:23.300
 But in Python 1, we didn't do that.

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:24.900
 It was an array.

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:37.000
 And the only place that we have to worry about its dynamic nature, the only place we have to worry about its dynamic nature is in the append, right?

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.800
 Where we reallocate it.

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:45.300
 So everything we're doing here is a simple for loop.

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:50.400
 So like even the del command here, the del basically says, let's free all those little items.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:57.900
 Let's free those character strings with a for loop for i equals zero, i less than self length, i plus plus.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:03.000
 Again, a beginning C programmer can understand this code.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:09.000
 And if we look at the C code in KRList_del, we just see a while loop.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.100
 And remember, you had to do these in a certain order.

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:15.900
 And so the whole free and I talked about all this stuff.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:18.900
 The fact that you got to do it in a certain order.

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:24.400
 Well, this is pretty simple, right?

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:27.600
 So it frees each of the items.

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:35.100
 It's for i equals zero in P1List_del, you free each of the characters strings that we point to.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:40.400
 Then we free the array that's got those pointers, which are now valid because we got rid of them.

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:42.500
 And then you free the object itself.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:54.300
 And so to some degree, one can appreciate the simplicity of what Guido did in this by going with arrays.

00:12:54.300 --> 00:13:06.000
 And again, the key thing that misled me or that Guido just took a different approach, it really came down to Realloc.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:12.600
 And so he believed in, I was trained to not think about Realloc as plan A.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:18.200
 And so I thought linked lists were plan A because then you don't have to do so many Reallocs.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:22.400
 And he was like, I want an array and Realloc says it's going to do this for me.

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:23.500
 And away we go.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:35.800
 So I encourage you to take a look at P1List and KRList and put them in two windows next to each other and sort of compare and contrast.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:42.800
 And what I really want you to do as you're comparing and contrasting is I want you to think about the complexity of writing,

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:56.100
 debugging, and then later the complexity of understanding and how much knowledge a programmer has to understand to be able to make sense of these two bits of code.

00:13:56.100 --> 00:14:03.200
 And again, for those of us computer scientists for whom linked lists are very natural, we just write this stuff.

00:14:03.200 --> 00:14:07.400
 I can write it pretty fast, but that doesn't mean that it's the easiest to learn.

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:09.400
 So away we go.

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:12.100
 And so I hope you found this comparison interesting.

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:14.100
 Cheers.

